President Trump Visits Site of Northern California's Deadly Camp Fire

By Pam Wright

2 days ago

weather.com

01:41

President Trump Tours Fire Ravaged California

President Donald Trump tours the devastation in California with California Gov. Jerry Brown and Gov.-elect Gavin Newsom.

At a Glance

  • Seventy-one people have died in the fire and more than 1,000 are reported missing.
  • Trump was joined by California Gov. Jerry Brown and Gov.-elect Gavin Newsom.

President Donald Trump arrived in Northern California on Saturday to visit with first responders and state officials, as well as to witness firsthand the devastation left behind by the state's deadliest and most destructive wildfire on record.

Seventy-one people have died in the fire and more than 1,000 are reported missing, although authoritiesÂ stress that many will likely turn up unharmed. The fire has also destroyed more than 9,800 homes and, at its height, displaced 52,000 people.

Before embarkingÂ on Air Force One bound for Beale Air Force Base north of Sacramento early Saturday, the president tweeted that he looked "forward to being with our brave firefighters, first responders and FEMA, along with the many brave people of California. We are with you all the way â God Bless you all!"

Upon arrival, the president took a helicopter tour of the devastated landscape.

Trump was welcomed by Gov. Jerry Brown and Gov.-elect Gavin Newsom. He was also greeted by Paradise Mayor Jody Jones when he arrived Chico before he toured neighborhoods in Paradise, a city of 27,000 that wasÂ largely wiped out by the fire. Also on the visit was FEMA director Brock Long.

Trump said seeing the devastation has not changed his opinion on the link between increasing wildfires and climate change.

âNo, no, I have a strong opinion," he said.

Ahead of the visit, Brown and Newsom appeared in favor of the president's visit, saying that it was time "to pull together for the people of California," the Associated Press reports.

The president's trip was not entirely welcomed by some who believe his comments including a in a recent tweet condemning California's forest management practices were incorrect and unfair.Â 

"There is no reason for these massive, deadly and costly forest fires in California except that forest management is so poor," Trump tweeted on Nov. 10. "Billions of dollars are given each year, with so many lives lost, all because of gross mismanagement of the forests. Remedy now, or no more Fed payments!"

On Friday, Trump taped a segment for "Fox News Sunday" in whichÂ he feigned surprise to see images of firefighters removing dried brush near a fire, adding, "This should have been all raked out," AP reported.

When asked if he thought climate change had anything to do with the wildfires, he responded: "Maybe it contributes a little bit. The big problem we have is management."

Trump said Friday that the visit to Northern California on Saturday would include more discussions on issues of forest management.Â 

Maggie Crowder of Magalia, a hard-hit area, told the Associated Press she did not feel the president should come considering the "insults" he said about the state.

"If you insult people, then you go visit them, how do you think you're going to be accepted? You're not going to have a parade," she said.

Firefighters were torn. Many said the president's trip was the mark of a good leader but felt the insults were uncalled for.Â 

In the days that followed the Nov. 10 tweet and as the death toll continued to climb, Trump posted numerous tweets praising firefighters, first responders and the Federal Emergency Management Administration, noting that "we at the White House are with" Gov. Brown and "the people of California, all the way!"

As of Saturday, the fire that began on Nov. 8 had consumed a record-breaking 231 square miles and was 55 percent contained.
